'''Calponin 3. acidic''' is a [[protein]] that in humans is encoded by the ''CNN3'' [[gene]].

The ''CNN3'' gene is located at 1p22-p21<ref name="pmid8526917">{{cite journal | vauthors = Maguchi M, Nishida W, Kohara K, Kuwano A, Kondo I, Hiwada K | title = Molecular cloning and gene mapping of human basic and acidic calponins | journal = Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications | volume = 217 | issue = 1 | pages = 238–44 | year = 1995 | pmid = 8526917 | doi = 10.1006/bbrc.1995.2769 }}</ref> in the human chromosomal genome. ''CNN3'' gene contains 7 exons and encodes calponin 3, a 36.4-kDa protein consisting of 329 amino acids with isoelectric point (pI) of 5.84. Calponin 3 is known as acidic calponin. Among three isoforms of calponin, less is known for the gene regulation and function of calponin 3. Nonetheless, much has been learned from extensive studies on the homologous genes ''CNN1'' and ''CNN2'' that encode [[calponin 1]] and [[calponin 2]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu R, Jin JP | year =  2016 | title = Calponin Isoforms CNN1, CNN2 and CNN3: Regulators for Actin Cytoskeleton Functions in Smooth Muscle and Non-Muscle Cells. | journal = Gene | doi=10.1016/j.gene.2016.02.040 }}</ref>

== Evolution ==
[[File:CNN3 wikipage.jpg|thumb|382x382px|
'''Figure 1.''' Evolutionary lineage of vertebrate calponin 3 isoforms deduced from alignment of amino acid sequences.
]]''CNN3'' is one of the three homologous calponin isoform genes. Calponin 3 is significantly diverged from calponin 1 and calponin 2 in the C terminal variable region. The higher degree of divergence among vertebrate ''CNN3'' genes than that in the ''CNN1'' and ''CNN2'' gene families suggests possibly earlier emergence of ''CNN3'', indicating that calponin 3 may represent a prototype of calponin ancestral of the three present-day isoforms (Fig. 1).

== Structure-function relationships ==

The primary structure of calponin 3 is similar as that of calponin 1 and calponin 2, consisting of a conserved N-terminal calponin homology (CH) domain, a conserved middle region containing two actin-binding sites, and a C-terminal variable region. The unique length amino acid sequence of the C-terminal segment of the three calponin isoforms are responsible for their size and overall charge differences.

Calponin 3 has been shown to participate in actin cytoskeleton-based activities such as that in embryonic development<ref name="Shibukawa_2010">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shibukawa Y, Yamazaki N, Kumasawa K, Daimon E, Tajiri M, Okada Y, Ikawa M, Wada Y | title = Calponin 3 regulates actin cytoskeleton rearrangement in trophoblastic cell fusion | journal = Molecular Biology of the Cell | volume = 21 | issue = 22 | pages = 3973–84 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20861310 | pmc = 2982094 | doi = 10.1091/mbc.E10-03-0261 }}</ref> and myogenesis.<ref name="Daimon_2013">{{cite journal | vauthors = Daimon E, Shibukawa Y, Wada Y | title = Calponin 3 regulates stress fiber formation in dermal fibroblasts during wound healing | journal = Archives of Dermatological Research | volume = 305 | issue = 7 | pages = 571–84 | year = 2013 | pmid = 23545751 | doi = 10.1007/s00403-013-1343-8 }}</ref> Unlike calponin 1, calponin 3 has little effect on actomyosin Mg<sup>2+</sup>-ATPase activity and does not cause actin filaments bundling at the same condition as calponin 1 does.<ref name="pmid12033495">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fujii T, Yabe S, Nakamura K, Koizumi Y | title = Functional analysis of rat acidic calponin | journal = Biological & Pharmaceutical Bulletin | volume = 25 | issue = 5 | pages = 573–9 | year = 2002 | pmid = 12033495 | doi = 10.1248/bpb.25.573 }}</ref>

== Tissue distribution ==

Calponin 3 is found in the brain with expression in [[neurons]],<ref name="pmid7493632">{{cite journal | vauthors = Represa A, Trabelsi-Terzidis H, Plantier M, Fattoum A, Jorquera I, Agassandian C, Ben-Ari Y, der Terrossian E | title = Distribution of caldesmon and of the acidic isoform of calponin in cultured cerebellar neurons and in different regions of the rat brain: an immunofluorescence and confocal microscopy study | journal = Experimental Cell Research | volume = 221 | issue = 2 | pages = 333–43 | year = 1995 | pmid = 7493632 | doi = 10.1006/excr.1995.1383 }}</ref><ref name="pmid7864813">{{cite journal | vauthors = Trabelsi-Terzidis H, Fattoum A, Represa A, Dessi F, Ben-Ari Y, der Terrossian E | title = Expression of an acidic isoform of calponin in rat brain: western blots on one- or two-dimensional gels and immunolocalization in cultured cells | journal = The Biochemical Journal | volume = 306 | issue = 1| pages = 211–5 | year = 1995 | pmid = 7864813 | pmc = 1136503 | doi = 10.1042/bj3060211}}</ref> [[astrocytes]],<ref name="pmid11134639">{{cite journal | vauthors = Agassandian C, Plantier M, Fattoum A, Represa A, der Terrossian E | title = Subcellular distribution of calponin and caldesmon in rat hippocampus | journal = Brain Research | volume = 887 | issue = 2 | pages = 444–9 | year = 2000 | pmid = 11134639 | doi = 10.1016/s0006-8993(00)03030-4}}</ref> and [[neuroglia|glial cells]],<ref name="pmid8758957">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferhat L, Charton G, Represa A, Ben-Ari Y, der Terrossian E, Khrestchatisky M | title = Acidic calponin cloned from neural cells is differentially expressed during rat brain development | journal = The European Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 8 | issue = 7 | pages = 1501–9 | year = 1996 | pmid = 8758957 | doi = 10.1111/j.1460-9568.1996.tb01612.x}}</ref> where it may function in regulating the actin cytoskeleton with a proposed role in the plasticity of neural tissues.<ref name="pmid10457177">{{cite journal | vauthors = Plantier M, Fattoum A, Menn B, Ben-Ari Y, Der Terrossian E, Represa A | title = Acidic calponin immunoreactivity in postnatal rat brain and cultures: subcellular localization in growth cones, under the plasma membrane and along actin and glial filaments | journal = The European Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 11 | issue = 8 | pages = 2801–12 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10457177 | doi = 10.1046/j.1460-9568.1999.00702.x}}</ref><ref name="Ferhat_2003">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferhat L, Esclapez M, Represa A, Fattoum A, Shirao T, Ben-Ari Y | title = Increased levels of acidic calponin during dendritic spine plasticity after pilocarpine-induced seizures | journal = Hippocampus | volume = 13 | issue = 7 | pages = 845–58 | year = 2003 | pmid = 14620880 | doi = 10.1002/hipo.10136 }}</ref> Calponin 3 is also present in embryonic trophoblasts and [[myoblasts]] with functions in cell fusion during embryonic development and [[myogenesis]]<ref name="Shibukawa_2010"/><ref name="Daimon_2013"/> Calponin 3 is also expressed in [[B lymphocytes]].<ref name="Flemming_2015">{{cite journal | vauthors = Flemming A, Huang QQ, Jin JP, Jumaa H, Herzog S | title = A Conditional Knockout Mouse Model Reveals That Calponin-3 Is Dispensable for Early B Cell Development | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 10 | issue = 6 | pages = e0128385 | year = 2015 | pmid = 26046660 | pmc = 4457629 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0128385 }}</ref>

== Function ==

Calponin 3 was found in stress fibers of skin fibroblasts and myofibroblasts during wound healing. ''Cnn3'' knockdown in primary fibroblasts impaired stress fiber formation, resulting in decreased cell motility and contractile ability.<ref name="Daimon_2013"/>> Calponin 3 in the brain has a potential function in regulating actin filaments during neuronal remodeling.<ref name="pmid16358313">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rami G, Caillard O, Medina I, Pellegrino C, Fattoum A, Ben-Ari Y, Ferhat L | title = Change in the shape and density of dendritic spines caused by overexpression of acidic calponin in cultured hippocampal neurons | journal = Hippocampus | volume = 16 | issue = 2 | pages = 183–97 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16358313 | doi = 10.1002/hipo.20145 }}</ref> Calponin 3 was also found in dendritic spines of adult hippocampal neurons to regulate dendritic spine plasticity.<ref name="Ferhat_2003"/> While mice with systemic knockout of ''Cnn1''<ref name="pmid11112431">{{cite journal | vauthors = Takahashi K, Yoshimoto R, Fuchibe K, Fujishige A, Mitsui-Saito M, Hori M, Ozaki H, Yamamura H, Awata N, Taniguchi S, Katsuki M, Tsuchiya T, Karaki H | title = Regulation of shortening velocity by calponin in intact contracting smooth muscles | journal = Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications | volume = 279 | issue = 1 | pages = 150–7 | year = 2000 | pmid = 11112431 | doi = 10.1006/bbrc.2000.3909 }}</ref> or ''Cnn2'',<ref name="pmid18617524">{{cite journal | vauthors = Huang QQ, Hossain MM, Wu K, Parai K, Pope RM, Jin JP | title = Role of H2-calponin in regulating macrophage motility and phagocytosis | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 283 | issue = 38 | pages = 25887–99 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18617524 | pmc = 2533796 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M801163200 }}</ref> or both ''Cnn1'' and ''Cnn2'' survive to adulthood and fertile, systemic knockout of calponin 3 in mice results in embryonic and neonatal lethality due to defect in the development of central nervous system.<ref name="Flemming_2015"/> ''CNN3'' was found in the trophoblasts of human placenta and plays a role of negative regulator of trophoblast fusion. Knockdown or dissociation of calponin 3 from cytoskeleton in response to PKC phosphorylation promoted fusion of trophoblasts.<ref name="Shibukawa_2010"/>

Consistently, calponin 3 was also present in myoblasts as an inhibitory regulator of cell fusion. Overexpression of calponin 3 in mouse C<sub>2</sub>C<sub>12</sub> myoblasts inhibited cell fusion during ''in vitro'' differentiation, whereas ''Cnn3'' gene knockdown promoted cell fusion and the expression of skeletal muscle myosin. The inhibitory effect of calponin 3 was reversed upon phosphorylation by Rho-associated kinase 1/2 (ROCK1/2).<ref name="Shibukawa_2010"/>

